 Beaver dams punctuated the stream network, flooded large areas of the landscape
, and created hydrologic and soil conditions particularly well-suited to
 the life-history requirements of willows.
 During the latter half of the 1900s, willows declined in abundance and
 stature to the extent that they effectively disappeared from the landscape
 and were replaced by grasslands in riparian zones 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Houston:1982if,Snger_et_al_1994,Singer:1998mw"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change in riparian state from willow to grassland coincided with changes
 in the terrestrial food web and the disturbance regime.
 Throughout the 20th century, the northern range provided winter habitat
 for one of the largest migratory elk herds (
\emph on
Cervus elaphus) 
\emph default
in North America 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Houston:1982if"

\end_inset

.
